{{For|the politician Putta Sudhakar Yadav|Mydukur (Assembly constituency)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}} {{Infobox museum | name = Sudha Cars Museum | native_name = | native_name_lang = | logo = | logo_upright = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | image = Snap from Sudha Cars Museum Hyderabad 3767.JPG | image_upright = | alt = | caption = Sudha Cars Museum | map_type = India Telangana#India | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|17.3569907|78.4544072|display=inline}} | former_name = | established = 2010 | dissolved = | location = [[Hyderabad]], [[Telangana]], India | type = | accreditation = | key_holdings = | collections = | collection_size = | visitors = | founder = K. Sudhakar | director = | president = | ceo = | chairperson = | curator = | architect = | historian = | owner = | publictransit = | car_park = | parking = | network = | website = {{URL|http://sudhacars.com/}} | embedded = }}
'''Sudha Cars Museum''' is an automobile museum located in [[Hyderabad, India]].<ref name="strangesites">{{cite news|title=Strange sites |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/strange-sites/article4720637.ece |first=Anuradha |last=Goyal |date=18 May 2013 |work=[[The Hindu]] |accessdate=9 Aug 2016}}</ref><ref name="DM">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2377840/Indian-inventor-Sudhakar-Yadav-builds-700-road-legal-cars-shape-everyday-objects.html |title=Wacky Races! Indian inventor builds around 700 weird and wonderful road legal cars in the shape of everyday objects including a huge burger and an over-sized tennis ball |date=2 July 2013 |work=Daily Mail |accessdate=8 August 2016 |author= Rush, James}}</ref><ref name="IT">{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/auto/story/sudhakar-attempts-another-record-by-designing-26-ft-tall-car/1/501117.html |title=Sudhakar attempts another record by designing 26-ft tall car |date=17 October 2015 |work=Indian Today |accessdate=8 August 2016 |author= }}</ref><ref name="Red">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/slide-show/slide-show-1-auto-wacky-hand-made-cars-in-hyderabad-museum/20130111.htm |title=Wacky, hand-made cars in Hyderabad museum |date=11 January 2013 |work=Rediff |accessdate=8 August 2016 |author= Samal, Itishree }}</ref> The museum displays "crazy cars" that resemble everyday objects. These cars are handmade by Kanyaboyina Sudhakar (known mainly as '''K. Sudhakar''' or K. Sudhakar Yadav) who started it as his hobby in his school days and opened the dedicated museum in 2010.<ref>http://sudhacars.com/about-us.html</ref><ref>https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/car-designer-k-sudhakar-attempts-world-record-by-designing-26-ft-tall-car/articleshow/49335638.cms</ref><ref>http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-tricycle</ref>
== Exhibits == Sudhakar Yadav had an inclination towards motor cars and mechanics since childhood. He created his first car at the age of 14 collecting the necessary articles from junkyards. His name was in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' in 2005 for the largest tricycle. On 1 July 2005 he rode the largest tricycle in Hyderabad which had an overall height of {{Convert|12.67|m}}. The tricycle's wheel diameter was {{Convert|5.18|m}} and the length was {{Convert|11.37|m}}.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-tricycle | title=Largest tricycle | publisher=Guinness World Records | date=16 August 2016 | accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name="BBCrecord">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-34464790 | title=India man eyes record with 26-foot-high car | work=BBC | date=7 October 2015 | accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref> Yadav and his museum are mentioned in the ''[[Limca Book of Records]]'' and have also been featured on ''[[Ripley's Believe It or Not!]]''<ref name="NewsMinute">{{cite web | url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/lives/496 | title=India's own version of Ripley's Believe It or Not; this car museum in Hyderabad has it all! | work=[[The News Minute]] | date=21 March 2015 | accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>
All the exhibits of the museum accompany a plaque giving information of the make of the car, the time it took to manufacture and the maximum speed it can attain. The museum also has the smallest double decker bus in the world which can accommodate 10 people. Twelve different motor cycles in small size are on display of which the smallest is {{Convert|33|cm}} in height and can be driven at the speed of {{Convert|30|km/h}}.<ref name="NewsMinute"/>
Yadav stated that some of the cars are created keeping special occasions in mind. For [[International Women's Day|Women's Day]], he designed a car shaped like a [[handbag]] and [[stiletto]] that was powered by a 6cc engine. For [[Bal Diwas]] (Children's Day), he designed cars based on a [[pen]], [[pencil]] and [[Pencil sharpener|sharpener]]. A [[condom]] shaped car was unveiled to commemorate [[World AIDS Day]].<ref name="causecraftscar">{{cite news|title=Cause crafts car |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/from-social-work-to-plain-creativity-representational-automobile-design-spans-a-wide-range/article6419538.ece |first=Prince |last=Frederick |date=26 September 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |location=Chennai |accessdate=16 Aug 2016}}</ref>
The homemade cars cost around {{GBP}}1,000{{endash}}{{GBP}}1,800 (₹85,000{{endash}}₹150,000) for manufacturing; but are not for sale. The cars are often brought out of the museum for road shows where people can see them being driven.<ref name="Tele">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/howaboutthat/11113517/Crazy-car-museum-Sudhakar-Yadavs-collection-of-homemade-vehicles.html |title=Crazy car museum: Sudhakar Yadav's collection of homemade vehicles |date= |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=8 August 2016 |author= }}</ref>
